\par }\pard\plain \s16\ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {It\rquote s possible for a character to have two skills
 that work well together. In general, having 5 or more ranks in one skill gives the character a +2 bonus on skill checks with each of its synergistic skills, as noted in the skill description. In some cases, this bonus applies only to specific uses of the
 skill in question, and not to all checks. Some skills provide benefits on other checks made by a character, such as those checks required to use certain class features.
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\cf0 
\par ABILITY CHECKS
\par }{\fs20\cf0 Sometimes a character tries to do something to which no specific skill really applies. In these cases, you make an ability check. An ability check is a roll of 1d20 plus the appropriate ability modifier. Essentially, you\rquote 
re making an untrained skill check. 
\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs18\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20 In some cases, an action is a straight test of one\rquote s ability with no luck involved. Just as you wouldn\rquote 
t make a height check to see who is taller, you don\rquote t make a Strength check to see who is stronger.
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs36\cf0 
\par SKILL DESCRIPTIONS
\par }{\fs20\cf0 This section describes each skill, including common uses and typical modifiers. Characters can sometimes use skills for purposes other than those noted here.
\par Here is the format for skill descriptions.
\par }{\cf0 
\par SKILL NAME
\par }{\fs20\cf0 The skill name line includes (in addition to the name of the skill) the following information.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Key Ability:}{\fs20\cf0  The abbreviation of the ability whose modifier applies to the skill check. }{\i\fs20\cf0 Exception: }{\fs20\cf0 Speak Language has \'93None\'94
 as its key ability because the use of this skill does not require a check.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Trained Only:}{\fs20\cf0  If this notation is included in the skill name line, you must have at least 1 rank in the sk
ill to use it. If it is omitted, the skill can be used untrained (with a rank of 0). If any special notes apply to trained or untrained use, they are covered in the Untrained section (see below).
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Armor Check Penalty:}{\fs20\cf0  If this notation is included in the skill name line, an armor check penalty applies (when appropriate) to checks using this skill. If this entry is absent, an armor check penalty does not apply.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s15\ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs18\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20\cf0 The skill name line is followed by a general description of what using the skill represents. After 
the description are a few other types of information:
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\fs20\cf0 Check:}{\fs20\cf0  What a character (\'93you\'94
 in the skill description) can do with a successful skill check and the check\rquote s DC.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Action:}{\fs20\cf0  The type of action using the skill requires, or the amount of time required for a check.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Try Again:}{\fs20\cf0  Any conditions that apply to successive attempts to use the skill successfully. If the skill doesn\rquote 
t allow you to attempt the same task more than once, or if failure carries an inherent penalty (such as with the Climb skill), you can\rquote 
t take 20. If this paragraph is omitted, the skill can be retried without any inherent penalty, other than the additional time required.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Special:}{\fs20\cf0  Any extra facts that apply to the skill, such as special effects deriving from its use or bonuses that certain characters receive because of class, feat choices, or race.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Synergy:}{\fs20\cf0  Some skills grant a bonus to the use of one or more other skills because of a synergistic effect. This entry, when present, indicates what bonuses this skill may grant or receive because of such synergies. See Table 4
\endash 5 for a complete list of bonuses granted by synergy between skills (or between a skill and a class feature).
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Restriction:}{\fs20\cf0  The full utility of certain skills is restricted to characters of certain classes or characters who possess certain feats. This entry indicates whether any such restrictions exist for the skill.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Untrained:}{\fs20\cf0  This entry indicates what a character without at least 1 rank in the skill can do with it. If this entry doesn\rquote t appear, it means that the skill functio
ns normally for untrained characters (if it can be used untrained) or that an untrained character can\rquote t attempt checks with this skill (for skills that are designated as \'93Trained Only\'94).
\par }{\cf0 
\par APPRAISE }{\fs20\cf0 (INT)
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Check:}{\fs20\cf0  You can appraise common or well-known objects with a DC 12 Appraise check. Failure means that you estimate the value at 50% to 150% (2d6+3 times 10%,) of its actual value.
\par Appraising a rare or exotic item requires a successful check against DC 15, 20, or higher. If the check is successful, you estimate the value correctly; failure means you cannot estimate the item\rquote s value.
\par A magnifying glass gives you a +2 circumstance bonus on Appraise checks involving any item that is small or highly detailed, such as a gem. A merchant\rquote s scale gives you a +2 circums
tance bonus on Appraise checks involving any items that are valued by weight, including anything made of precious metals.
\par These bonuses stack.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Action:}{\fs20\cf0  Appraising an item takes 1 minute (ten consecutive full-round actions).
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Try Again:}{\fs20\cf0  No. You cannot try again on the same object, regardless of success.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Special:}{\fs20\cf0  A dwarf gets a +2 racial bonus on Appraise checks that are related to stone or metal items because dwarves are familiar with valuable items of all kinds (especially those made of stone or metal).
\par The master of a raven familiar gains a +3 bonus on Appraise checks.
\par A character with the Diligent feat gets a +2 bonus on Appraise checks.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Synergy:}{\fs20\cf0  If you have 5 ranks in any Craft skill, you gain a +2 bonus on Appraise checks related to items made with that Craft skill.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Untrained:}{\fs20\cf0  For common items, failure on an untrained check means no estimate. For rare items, success means an estimate of 50% to 150% (2d6+3 times 10%).
