\par CRAFT }{\fs20\cf0 (INT)
\par Like Knowledge, Perform, and Profession, Craft is actually a number of separate skills. You could have several Craft skills, each with its own ranks, each purchased as a separate skill.
\par A Craft skill is specifically focused on creating something. If nothing is created by the endeavor, it probably falls under the heading of a Profession skill.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Check:}{\fs20\cf0  You can practice your trade and make a decent living, earning about half your check result in gold pieces per week of dedicated work. You know how to use the tools of your trade, how to perform the craft\rquote 
s daily tasks, how to supervise untrained helpers, and how to handle common problems. (Untrained laborers and assistants earn an average of 1 silver piece per day.)
\par The basic function of the Craft skill, however, is to allow you to make an item of the appropriate type. The DC depends on the complexity of the item to 
be created. The DC, your check results, and the price of the item determine how long it takes to make a particular item. The item\rquote s finished price also determines the cost of raw materials.
\par In some cases, the }{\i\fs20\cf0 fabricate }{\fs20\cf0 spell can be used to achieve the resu
lts of a Craft check with no actual check involved. However, you must make an appropriate Craft check when using the spell to make articles requiring a high degree of craftsmanship.
\par A successful Craft check related to woodworking in conjunction with the casting of the }{\i\fs20\cf0 ironwood }{\fs20\cf0 spell enables you to make wooden items that have the strength of steel.
\par When casting the spell }{\i\fs20\cf0 minor creation}{\fs20\cf0 , you must succeed on an appropriate Craft check to make a complex item.
\par All crafts require artisan\rquote s tools to give the best chance of success. If improvised tools are used, the check is made with a \endash 2 circumstance penalty. On the other hand, masterwork artisan\rquote 
s tools provide a +2 circumstance bonus on the check.
\par To determine how much time and money it takes to make an item, follow these steps.
\par 1. Find the item\rquote s price. Put the price in silver pieces (1 gp = 10 sp).
\par 2. Find the DC from the table below.
\par 3. Pay one-third of the item\rquote s price for the cost of raw materials.
\par 4. Make an appropriate Craft check representing one week\rquote s work. If the check succeeds, multiply your check result by the DC. If the result \'d7 the DC equals the price of the item in sp, then you have completed the item. (If the result \'d7
 the DC equals double or triple the price of the item in silver pieces, then you\rquote ve completed the task in one-half or one-third of the time. Other multiples of the DC reduce the time in the same manner.) If the result \'d7 the DC doesn\rquote 
t equal the price, then it represents the progress you\rquote ve made this week. Record the result and make a new Craft check for the next week. Each week, you make more progress until your total reaches the price of the item in silver pieces.
\par If you fail a check by 4 or less, you make no progress this week.
\par If you fail by 5 or more, you ruin half the raw materials and have to pay half the original raw material cost again.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Progress by the Day: }{\fs20\cf0 You can make checks by the day instead of by the week. In this case your progress (check result \'d7 DC) is in copper pieces instead of silver pieces.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Creating Masterwork Items: }{\fs20\cf0 You can make a masterwork item\emdash 
a weapon, suit of armor, shield, or tool that conveys a bonus on its use through its exceptional craftsmanship, not through being magical. To create a masterwork item, you create the masterwork component as if it were a separ
ate item in addition to the standard item. The masterwork component has its own price (300 gp for a weapon or 150 gp for a suit of armor or a shield) and a Craft DC of 20. Once both the standard component and the masterwork component are completed, the ma
sterwork item is finished. }{\i\fs20\cf0 Note: }{\fs20\cf0 The cost you pay for the masterwork component is one-third of the given amount, just as it is for the cost in raw materials.
